{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}
[[File:Mrs Graham's XI in 1895.jpg|thumb|280px|The British Ladies Football Club North Team - Mrs Graham's XI was a women's football team (in 1895)]]
'''Mrs Graham's XI''' was a women's [[association football|football]] team formed by [[Helen Matthews]] in [[Edinburgh, Scotland]] in 1881. It is considered the first British women's football team and a pioneering team in the history of the sport.<ref name="gwb_2013">{{cite book|last1=Tate|first1=Tim|title=Girls With Balls: The Secret History of Women's Football|date=2013|publisher=John Blake|isbn=1782196862|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vYknAgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Girls+with+Balls%22+Tate&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjHj-OYjf_SAhWmh1QKHXUxCJkQ6AEIGjAA#v=onepage&q=%22Girls%20with%20Balls%22%20Tate&f=false}}</ref> Because it was not safe for women to play football without harassment, the players used pseudonyms to protect their identities. Matthews, also a goalkeeper for the team, claimed to be "Mrs Graham".<ref name="gwb_2013" />

==History==
The first record of the team coming together to play football occurred on 9 May 1881, at Edinburgh's [[Easter Road Stadium]]. The match was billed as a Scotland v England international.<ref name="gwb_2013" /><ref name=BTF>Domeneghetti, R. (2014) ''From the Back Page to the Front Room: Football's journey through the English media'' [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lmWLBQAAQBAJ&lpg=PT156&dq=british%20ladies%20football%20team&pg=PT155#v=onepage&q=british%20ladies%20football%20team&f=false page 155] Ockley Books. {{ISBN|1783015586}} Retrieved February 2015</ref>

Just over a week later, on 20 May 1881,<ref name="gwb_2013" /> the teams played in Glasgow in front of 5,000 spectators. The match was abandoned in the 55th minute after a violent pitch invasion during which the women were "roughly jostled", and chased by a mob as they left the grounds.<ref name="gwb_2013" /><ref name=BTF/> Further games resulted in similar pitch invasions, which soon resulting in ending this early attempt to introduce women's football.<ref name=UB/>

The press coverage, which would dominate coverage of women's football for the next century, was clearly established in 1881: barely disguised contempt regarding player appearance, including costume, and the standard of play,<ref name=BTF/> overlaid with a certainty that football was a rough man's game unsuitable for women.<ref name=UB>Laycock, S. & Laycock, P. (2014) ''Unexpected Britain'' [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=fKelBAAAQBAJ&lpg=PT199&dq=british%20ladies%20football%20team&pg=PT199#v=onepage&q=british%20ladies%20football%20team&f=false page 199] Amberley Publishing. {{ISBN|1445632845}} Retrieved February 2015</ref>

An attempt to form a new club was made by Matthews<ref name=DSS>Tomlinson, A. (2010) ''A Dictionary of Sports Studies'' [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=r_Ujf9-TmBUC&lpg=PA490&dq=british%20ladies%20football%20team&pg=PA490#v=onepage&q=british%20ladies%20football%20team&f=false page 490] Oxford University Press. {{ISBN|019921381X}} Retrieved February 2015</ref> with [[Nettie Honeyball]] (also a pseudonym) founding the [[British Ladies' Football Club]] on 1 January 1895.<ref name=UB/> 

